snippet.textDisplay: These leftwing "celebrities"ONLY exist for my entertainment. Some of you are great eye candy. Some of you can deliver a line with such conviction that you bring tears to my eyes. Some of you can scare the crap out of me. Others make me laugh. But you all have one thing in common, you ONLY have a place in my world to entertain me. That’s it. You make your living pretending to be someone else. Playing dress up like a 6 year old. You live in a make believe world in front of a camera. And often, when you are away from one too. Your entire existence depends on my patronage. I’ll crank the organ ; you dance. I don’t really care where you stand on issues. Honestly, your stance matters far less to me than that of my neighbor. You see, you aren’t real. I turn off my TV or shut down my computer and you cease to exist in my world. Once I am done with you, I can put you back in your little box until I want you to entertain me again. I don’t care that you think about our president, or ANYTHING, for that matter.. But I bet you looked great saying it. Make me laugh, or cry. Scare me. But realize that the only words of yours that matter are scripted. I might agree with some of you from time to time, but it doesn’t matter. In my world, you exist solely for my entertainment. You people cannot possibly understand the frustrations "everyday" people have, in regards to our government. Your wealth is something 99.9% of the American people can only dream of. You,are not on our level.

Im not really agreeing with either side because something about both sides throws me off, I don’t really like the left because they’re all about things like “free to think and be whatever you like” which is a good thing of course, but in reality, if you’re not something that they agree with then they argue with you about it. It just seems like hypocrisy to me. They don’t respect your right to decide what you do and don’t like for yourself and they say that they’re against that way of thinking.

But that’s just my opinion, it shouldn’t affect or hurt anyone other then myself, if that affects you somewhat then I’m sorry but that’s just what I think. And I don’t think or know that I have the moral high ground because I know I don’t, and I think you should be careful about people who think they’re “in the right”. You never know what that person will do if they think they’re justified. But that’s just my opinion, you’re free to ignore it, like it or dislike it because that’s your basic human privilege; you where born with the ability to think for yourself.

snippet.textDisplay: I’m somewhere in the middle on this - I don’t think being an actor means someone can’t have a valid political opinion, as many right wing pundits and politicians like to proclaim as a way to discredit any high profile person who speaks out against them. The whole “stick to acting/singing, don’t talk about politics” thing is usually just a disingenuous way of saying “I disagree with you so I want you to shut up”. I mean who IS allowed to have an opinion - actors aren’t “qualified” to have an opinion but the average rando on the street is, even if they know nothing? However, I certainly agree with Pie (and Gervais) that Hollywood shouldn’t be immune to criticism and hypocrisy should be pointed out.  The best thing Ricky Gervais does is refuse to be intimidated by the PC brigade who want to crucify him for simply telling the truth. He’s not right wing, he’s actually very liberal, by the definition of what liberal used to mean, before it became the weird regressive extremism that it is now.  Gervais and most of Hollywood actually have the same views on most major political things (I.e., that Trump is a dangerous idiot, climate change is real, and other “liberal” views) but somehow Gervais is being portrayed as the enemy because he refuses to tiptoe around the obsession with faux diversity and extreme leftist “tolerance.”

snippet.textDisplay:
Not one of Walker's best skits - firstly I don't really get why he cares, as he points out the world is literally on fire and actual fascism is on the rise across the globe. Secondly this is all over the place in terms of being actually true - it seems obvious to me that TV and film actually does a way better job of raising up people from working class backgrounds than most other industries. I'd bet a penny to a pound that there are a higher proportion of actors born in working class families than CEOs in any industry you name of the top of your head.


Is the film and TV industry better at raising up working class people than most other industries - probably.
Is it a bad thing that these people are trying to use their elevated positions to advocate for a more egalitarian world or raising issues of political significance in the public consciousness - probably not


If you're trying to make a political point with comedy like Walker unarguably is doing then these things matter. I generally like Walker but when he jumps on the free speech soapbox it almost always leads to a skit that just isn't very funny and to me usually sounds like he's totally missing the point. In this case that there's a world of difference between people saying 'What Gervais said is demonstrably wrong, here's why he shouldn't have said that' and 'Gervais shouldn't be allowed to say that'.


A comedian can make jokes which are based on fallacious or lazy ideas - they regularly do - and a journalist can seriously refute the thinking that leads to the those jokes and here's the important point: both of those things are ok and a healthy expression of free speech.

It only emerged in response to the #oscarssowhite hashtag a few years ago, and it seems to be a very controlled form of diversity, only really where deemed necessary, that suits a very out of touch Hollywood elite. The fact that Green Book won best picture last year with Sorry To Bother You getting snubbed is an example of this. If Hollywood really cared about diversity then there wouldn't be a separate category for foreign films, most of which, lets be honest, are light years better than the self congratulatory Oscar baiting shite churned out by studios in the run up to the awards season, and far more independent, low budget films would get the recognition they deserve
